hey <@U011E0VHPA4>!

I wrote an email a while ago to someone that had a similar question, hopefully it's useful:

&gt; _It's a useful tool, and I use it a lot for one purpose: quickly understanding the related topics that top-ranking articles also reference. If I want to write a canonical article on a particular topic, it's a useful complement to the qualitative research I run._
&gt; 
&gt; _With that said, I have some issues with the concept of the tool:_
&gt; 
&gt; _It can't differentiate between keywords that are repeatedly mentioned because they're integral to the topic, and those that are mentioned just because they're used as illustrative examples. If two articles use the same illustrative example - say "Apple" - Clearscope treats the use of the keyword "apple" as a ranking factor, even if the topic has no relevance to Apple. We regularly receive SEO briefs that are tantamount to plagiarism because they use Clearscope and don't make this distinction._
&gt; 
&gt; _It encourages mindless "optimization" at the expense of good, well-structured writing. Trying to cram 15 keyword variants into an article gives me flashbacks to the bad old days of SEO, and it sends our writers a mixed signal - improving the Clearscope score usually degrades the quality of a piece._
&gt; 
&gt; _Customers take the Clearscope score at face value and assume that anything less than A+ sucks - despite the fact that most currently top-ranking content doesn't get an A+. Instead of critically evaluating the quality of the writing, the angle we've taken, and so on, they latch onto the score because it's easily understood and communicated._
&gt; 
&gt; _Ultimately, it creates copycat content. It's a tool for emulating existing search results, and encourages people to consolidate existing information instead of adding anything new to the topic. It's a good tool for writing "skyscraper content," but it's actively harmful for any other types of content._
...and the article the email inspired: <https://www.animalz.co/blog/copycat-content/>

tl;dr - useful if applied in the right way, with potential downsides for thoughtless useless
